50|$|The Armenian tarkhana {{is made up}} of matzoon {{and eggs}} mixed with half of wheat flour and half of starch. Small pieces of dough are {{prepared}} and dried and then kept in glass containers and uses mostly dry soups, dissolving in hot liquids. The Greek trahana contains only cracked wheat or a cous cous-like paste and fermented milk. The Turkish tarhana consists of cracked wheat (or flour), yoghurt, and vegetables fermented then dried. In Cyprus, it is considered a national specialty, and is often served with pieces of <b>haloumi</b> <b>cheese</b> in it.|$|E

